My next step should be a proxy manager then, on top of all the code refactoring of course. I've been looking around for a good NoSQL async supported server/client but no luck so far. I saw shelfdb but it was causing all sorts of problems. Might have to go mongo, or postgres, but I think they are too large for proxy management. What I plan on doing is something like this, incoming psuedocode:

```python
timeout = 30
def update_proxy_used(proxy):
    db('proxies').update({
            'proxy': proxy,
            'active': False,
            'last_used': time.time()
        }
    ).run()


def update_proxy_active(proxy):
    db('proxies').update({'proxy': proxy, 'active': True}).run()


def get_proxy():
    query = db('proxies').first(proxies['last_used'] > time.time() and proxies['active'] == False and proxies['banned'] == False)
    return query.run()


def insert_proxy():
    db('proxies').insert({
            'proxy': '127.0.0.1:1000',
            'active': False,
            'banned': False,
            'last_used': time.time()
        }
    ).run()


async def do_something_with_proxy():
    await asyncio.sleep(5)


async def main():
    await insert_proxy()
    proxy = await get_proxy()
    await update_proxy_active(proxy)
    await do_something_with_proxy()
    await update_proxy_used(proxy)
```

